<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">📖 Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">Yesterday: a list of factors. Today: a system.</p>
  <p>In Block 1 you listed five-plus factors that might affect whether a planet can support life. Today we make the move that the rest of this course depends on: those factors don't sit alone. They interact. A magnetic field protects an atmosphere. An atmosphere holds heat and shapes water cycles. Water shapes weather, weather shapes rocks, rocks shape carbon storage. Earth's habitability isn't a checklist — it's a system.</p>
  <p>The right unit of analysis from here on is <strong>Earth's four subsystems</strong>: the atmosphere (air), hydrosphere (water), geosphere (rock + interior), and biosphere (life). Each one interacts with the others through energy flows and matter cycles, and many of those interactions are <em>feedback loops</em> — relationships that either amplify a change (positive feedback) or push back toward stability (negative feedback). Systems thinking is the lens you'll use for every unit after this one too: weather, plate tectonics, hydrology, ecology, energy, sustainability. It all comes back to this move.</p>
  <p>The Systems Diagrammer AI partner launches today. It's a coach, not a drawing tool — it asks you the questions you'd ask yourself if you had more practice. The goal is that by exit ticket you have a defensible first systems diagram, drawn by you.</p>
</section>

